name: alchemy-logging
description: Application logging libraries with consistent semantics across c++, python, typescript, and go
contribution_justification: Non-trivial contribution file in repository: <https://github.com/IBM/alchemy-logging/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md>.
contribution_requirements_justification: Currently, only the typescript implementation supports linting and it is not automated (https://github.com/IBM/alchemy-logging/blob/main/src/ts/tslint.json). This may be improved in the future: https://github.com/IBM/alchemy-logging/issues/156
license_location_justification: Non-trivial license location file in repository: <https://github.com/IBM/alchemy-logging/blob/main/LICENSE>.
floss_license_justification: The MIT license is approved by the Open Source Initiative (OSI).
floss_license_osi_justification: The MIT license is approved by the Open Source Initiative (OSI).
documentation_basics_justification: Some documentation basics file contents found.
documentation_interface_justification:
* Higher order APIs for all languages are described in the top-level README: https://github.com/IBM/alchemy-logging#implementations
* `python`: https://github.com/IBM/alchemy-logging/blob/main/src/python/README.md#usage
* `typescript`: https://github.com/IBM/alchemy-logging/blob/main/src/ts/README.md#configuration
* `go`: https://github.com/IBM/alchemy-logging/blob/main/src/go/README.md#standard-configuration
* `c++`: https://github.com/IBM/alchemy-logging/blob/main/src/cpp/README.md#configuration
repo_public_justification: Repository on GitHub, which provides public git repositories with URLs.
repo_track_justification: Repository on GitHub, which uses git. git can track the changes, who made them, and when they were made.
repo_interim_justification: The workflow for this project involves submitting PRs against `main`, but releases are manually cut by creating GitHub releases which create a `git tag` at the given point in the history of the `main` branch.
repo_distributed_justification: Repository on GitHub, which uses git. git is distributed.
version_unique_justification:
Release management is handled independently using semantic versioning for each language release. Each language is released by creating a GitHub Release (and corresponding `git tag`) formatted as `<prefix>-<major>.<minor>.<patch>`. The `prefix` for each language is:

* python: `py`
* typescript: `ts`
* go: `go`
* c++: `cpp`

https://github.com/IBM/alchemy-logging/releases
version_tags_justification: (see description above of tagging format for independent releases)
release_notes_vulns_justification: By design, the released artifacts have zero dependencies in all language implementations. If that changes and CVEs are found against such release-dependencies (as opposed to test dependencies), they will be indicated in the Change Log for the corresponding release
vulnerability_report_process_justificati:
https://github.com/IBM/alchemy-logging/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md#reporting-bugs

The repository also leverages Dependabot for automated dependency scanning. The project maintains zero dependencies (excluding test dependencies) for all language implementations except c++ (by design), so any vulnerabilities will be against the code itself and should therefore be filed as bugs. For c++, vulnerability reports will need to be manually pulled.
build_justification:
* Top-level CI/CD is implemented using GitHub Actions: https://github.com/IBM/alchemy-logging/tree/main/.github/workflows
* Each language project has its own build system which includes building artifacts, running unit tests, and pushing release artifacts (on release only)
build_common_tools_justification:
* c++: CMake (https://github.com/IBM/alchemy-logging/blob/main/src/cpp/CMakeLists.txt) and Docker (https://github.com/IBM/alchemy-logging/blob/main/src/cpp/Dockerfile)
* go: go toolchain (https://github.com/IBM/alchemy-logging/blob/main/src/go/go.mod) and Docker (https://github.com/IBM/alchemy-logging/blob/main/src/go/Dockerfile)
* python: pip/setuptools (https://github.com/IBM/alchemy-logging/blob/main/src/python/setup.py) and Docker (https://github.com/IBM/alchemy-logging/blob/main/src/python/Dockerfile)
* typescript: node (https://github.com/IBM/alchemy-logging/blob/main/src/ts/package.json) and Docker (https://github.com/IBM/alchemy-logging/blob/main/src/ts/Dockerfile)
test_invocation_justification: Each language implements a dockerized development and `ci` scripts that are run within that environment can execute the unit tests. Those scripts may be used natively outside of the dockerized environment as well. Additionally, each language has a CONTRIBUTING.md file that indicates how to run tests for that language.
test_most_justification: Currently, coverage reporting is implemented for python, typescript, and go, but not c++. Additionally, the coverage results are not a gating function for accepting changes. This issue suggests that we strengthen this: https://github.com/IBM/alchemy-logging/issues/157
test_policy_justification: As the sole maintainer of the project, this will be explicitly checked for any significant changes (including from myself)
tests_are_added_justification: All releases run the unit tests against the produced artifacts
tests_documented_added_justification: This should be documented better. Issue to fix: https://github.com/IBM/alchemy-logging/issues/158
warnings_justification: Implemented in https://github.com/IBM/alchemy-logging/pull/160 by adding `-Wall -Werror` to `c++`, `-Werror` to `python`, and `npm run lint` to `typescript`
know_secure_design_justification: As the primary developer, I have extensive experience building libraries and cloud microservices within IBM to be deployed into multicloud environments with strict security requirements (e.g. IBM SPbD)
crypto_published_justification: There is no cryptography in this project.
delivery_mitm_justification:
This project delivers using the standard language-appropriate package management for each language:

* go: go.mod using github
* c++: CPM (https://github.com/cpm-cmake/CPM.cmake) backed by github
* python: Pypi
* typescript: npm
discussion_justification: GitHub supports discussions on issues and pull requests.
hardened_site_justification: Found all required security hardening headers.
implementation_languages: C++, Python, Go, TypeScript, Shell, Dockerfile, CMake
